properties.name: Advice
properties.webBody:
This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for the Seven Creeks to Euroa.

MINOR FLOODING OCCURRING AT EUROA

Minor flood peak is likely during Saturday afternoon at Euroa.

In the 24 hours to 11:00 am Saturday, rainfall totals of 10-30 mm have been recorded in the Seven Creeks catchment.

Further rainfall totals of 10-20 mm are forecast for the remainder of Saturday into Sunday with isolated higher totals possible on elevated areas.

The situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary.

Seven Creeks to Euroa:

Minor flooding occurring along the Seven Creeks to Euroa.

The Seven Creeks at Euroa is currently at 2.55 metres and rising, above the minor flood level (2.50 metres).A peak around the minor flood level (2.50 metres) is likely in the Seven Creeks at Euroa Saturday afternoon.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do: 

  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/
Impacts in your area: 

  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Low lying caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 25/06/2023 03:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline. 
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.name: Advice
properties.webBody:
This Advice message is being issued for Cape Conran, Marlo.

  • Due to a whale carcass on the beach, there could be an increase in shark activity reported at Point Ricardo.
  • A whale carcass can attract sharks to the area and mean they are closer to the shore than normal.
  • While it is not uncommon for sharks to be present off the Victorian coast, you should exercise additional caution in the area.
Avoid the area. Stay informed and do not enter the water at closed beaches.
What you should do:

  • If you see sharks, report the sighting by calling Triple Zero (000) or notify lifesavers immediately if you are at a patrolled beach.
Staying safe at nearby beaches:
  • Always swim, dive or surf with a friend.
  • Swim between the red and yellow flags on patrolled beaches.
  • Don't swim in places where human or animal waste enters the water.
  • Keep away from large schools of fish, seals or other wildlife as these can attract sharks.
Impacts in your area:
  • Victorian Fisheries Authority is assisting wildlife officers and park rangers with the management of the whale carcass.
This message was issued by Victorian Fisheries Authority.

The next update is expected by 30/06/2023 05:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au 
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226 
  • VicEmergency app 
  • Facebook or Twitter 
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.   
Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline. 
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.webBody:
This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for the King River and Ovens River downstream of Rocky Point.

MINOR FLOODING EXPECTED TO PEAK AT DOCKER RD LATE SATURDAY MORNING, MINOR FLOODING POSSIBLE AT WANGARATTA OVERNIGHT SATURDAY INTO SUNDAY

In the 48 hours to 9 am Saturday, rainfall totals of 20 - 35 mm have been recorded in the Ovens and King River catchments.

Minor flooding is occurring at the King River at Docker Road, and may occur at the Ovens River at Wangaratta overnight Saturday into Sunday.

Further showers are forecast for the remainder of Saturday and into Sunday, with further rainfall totals of10-20mm possible over the weekend.

King River: 

Minor flooding is likely along the King River.

The King River at Docker Rd Bridge is currently at 3.79 metres and rising, with minor flooding. The King River at Docker Rd Bridge is likely to peak near 3.85 metres late Saturday morning with minor flooding.

Ovens River downstream of Rocky Point:

Minor flooding may occur along the Ovens River downstream of Rocky Point. 

The Ovens River at Wangaratta is currently at 11.26 metres and steady. The Ovens River is likely to peak around the minor flood level (11.9) overnight Saturday into Sunday.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do: 

  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Check out the Wangaratta Local Flood Guide for more flood information and what might happen, to help you be best informed and prepared, click here: Wangaratta Local Flood Guide 
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater. 
  • Floodwater is toxic - never play or swim in floodwater. 
  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes. You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
Impacts in your area: 

  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Riverside carparks will be closed at Bickerton St, Sydney Beach and Baker St.
  • Parks, hiking tracks and campgrounds are closed due to flooding. To find out more go to www.parkweb.vic.gov.au/safety/flood-affected-parks.
  • Low lying caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded.
  • For more information on road closures check the VicRoads website traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au.
  • Water will up to Yogi's chin in the Apex Park.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 25/06/2023 12:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline. 
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.
